# Nix Configuration Hardening Guide

> Generated by qsdev. This document provides system-level
> Nix security recommendations for administrators.

## DANGER: trusted-users

> **DANGER**: Adding users to `trusted-users` is **equivalent to giving them root access**.
> Trusted users can disable the sandbox, bypass signature verification, point the daemon
> at malicious binary caches, and escalate to full root privileges. The default
> `trusted-users = root` is the only safe value for production systems.
>
> devenv.sh documentation recommends adding your user to `trusted-users` for cache access.
> **Do not do this.** Use `trusted-substituters` and `trusted-public-keys` instead
> (see Section 3 below).

## Recommended Settings Summary

| Setting | Hardened Value | Purpose |
|---------|---------------|---------|
| `sandbox` | `true` | Isolate builds via Linux namespaces |
| `sandbox-fallback` | `false` | Fail loudly if sandbox unavailable |
| `require-sigs` | `true` | Reject unsigned binary cache paths |
| `trusted-users` | `root` | No non-root trusted users |
| `allowed-users` | `@wheel` | Restrict daemon access |
| `trusted-substituters` | (see below) | Scoped cache trust |
| `trusted-public-keys` | (see below) | Cache signing key trust |
| `accept-flake-config` | `false` | Reject flake nixConfig overrides |
| `filter-syscalls` | `true` | Block dangerous syscalls in sandbox |
| `restrict-eval` | `true` (CI only) | Restrict Nix evaluator file access |

## Setting-by-Setting Guide

### 1. sandbox = true, sandbox-fallback = false

The Nix build sandbox uses Linux kernel namespaces (PID, mount, network, IPC, UTS) to
isolate each build process. A sandboxed build can only see Nix store paths declared as
build inputs, a temporary build directory, private device nodes, and paths explicitly
listed in `sandbox-paths`. Network access is completely blocked for normal derivations.
Fixed-output derivations (FODs) bypass network isolation because they declare a content
hash upfront and need to fetch from the internet.

**Why `sandbox-fallback = false` matters:** The default `sandbox-fallback = true` means
that on a system where user namespaces are disabled (some hardened kernels, older kernels,
certain container runtimes), builds proceed without any isolation and **no warning is
emitted**. A developer could be running builds that access the entire host filesystem,
read environment variables, and make network connections, all while believing they are
sandboxed.

The `sandbox = relaxed` mode is equally dangerous: it allows any derivation with
`__noChroot = true` to skip sandboxing entirely. A malicious nixpkgs overlay or
third-party flake input could set this attribute on any derivation.

**What breaks:**

- Builds on kernels without user namespace support will fail instead of silently
  degrading. This is the correct behavior.
- Container-in-container scenarios (Nix inside Docker without `--privileged`) will fail.
  Fix: run the outer container with `--security-opt seccomp=unconfined` or use
  `SYS_ADMIN` capability.
- macOS uses `sandbox-exec` which is weaker than Linux namespaces. `sandbox = true` works
  but with documented limitations.

### 2. require-sigs = true

When Nix downloads a pre-built store path from a binary cache, the cache serves a
`.narinfo` file containing the NAR hash, size, references, and one or more Ed25519
signatures. Nix computes a fingerprint and verifies it against keys in
`trusted-public-keys`. With `require-sigs = true`, every non-content-addressed store path
must have a valid signature.

The default is already `true`, but we set it explicitly as defense against accidental
override. A flake's `nixConfig` or a `--option require-sigs false` flag could disable
this. Explicitly setting it in the system nix.conf ensures the daemon enforces it
regardless of what clients request.

**When a substituter serves an unsigned path:** the substitution is silently rejected and
Nix falls back to building the derivation from source. No error is displayed -- the build
simply takes longer. This can cause confusion when a cache appears to not work.

**What breaks:**

- Local store copies (`nix copy` between machines) where the source machine did not sign
  its store paths. Fix: generate a signing key pair with
  `nix-store --generate-binary-cache-key` and add the public key to
  `trusted-public-keys` on the destination.
- Custom Cachix or Attic caches without signing configured will have all substitutions
  rejected. Fix: configure cache signing in your cache infrastructure.

### 3. trusted-users = root (CRITICAL)

Trusted users can: specify arbitrary binary caches, import unsigned NARs into the store
(bypassing `require-sigs`), set any nix.conf option via `--option` (including
`sandbox = false`), add `sandbox-paths` gaining read access to arbitrary directories
during builds, and bypass `allowed-users` restrictions.

The Nix documentation is explicit: **"Adding a user to `trusted-users` is essentially
equivalent to giving that user root access to the system."**

**The devenv trap:** devenv.sh documentation commonly recommends
`trusted-users = root <username>` or `trusted-users = root @wheel` because devenv's
`nixConfig` specifies `extra-substituters` for its caches. For an untrusted user, these
substituters are ignored unless the user is in `trusted-users` (root-equivalent) OR the
substituter URL is in `trusted-substituters` (scoped permission). The devenv docs take the
path of least friction, granting root-equivalent access to solve a cache access problem.

**A user in `trusted-users` can escalate to root:** disable sandbox + point at malicious
cache + disable signature verification = arbitrary code execution as root via a crafted
derivation.

**Safe alternative for devenv cache access:**

Instead of `trusted-users = root youruser`, use:
```
trusted-substituters = https://devenv.cachix.org https://cachix.cachix.org
trusted-public-keys = devenv.cachix.org-1:w1cLUi8dv3hnoSPGAuibQv+f9TZLr6cv/Hm9XgU50cw= cachix.cachix.org-1:eWNHQldwUO7G2VkjpnjDbWwy4KQ/HNxht7H4SSoMckM=
```

This grants scoped cache access without granting any other elevated privileges.

### 4. allowed-users = @wheel

`allowed-users` controls which local users can connect to the Nix daemon's Unix domain
socket. Users not in this list cannot use Nix at all. The default `allowed-users = *`
lets any local user build arbitrary Nix expressions, consuming shared CPU, disk, and
network resources.

Set `allowed-users = root @wheel` on shared systems. For a single-user workstation,
`allowed-users = root <your-username>` is sufficient. Users not in the list get a daemon
connection error when running any Nix command.

### 5. trusted-substituters and trusted-public-keys

`trusted-substituters` lists binary cache URLs that unprivileged users are permitted to
enable. This is the scoped alternative to `trusted-users`: instead of granting
root-equivalent access so users can specify any cache, you pre-approve specific caches.

When an unprivileged user specifies a substituter, the daemon checks: (1) is the user in
`trusted-users`? If yes, allow any substituter. (2) Is the substituter URL in
`trusted-substituters`? If yes, allow it. (3) Otherwise, reject it silently.

`trusted-public-keys` lists Ed25519 public keys for verifying binary cache signatures.
A store path is accepted if it has a valid signature from at least one trusted key.

**Recommended caches for devenv.sh:**

| Cache | URL | Signing Key | Purpose |
|-------|-----|-------------|---------|
{{- range .DefaultCaches }}
| {{ .Name }} | {{ .URL }} | `{{ .PublicKey }}` | {{ .Purpose }} |
{{- end }}

Each cache URL is a trust surface. The signing key holder can provide arbitrary binaries
for any store path the cache serves. Minimize the number of caches to minimize the number
of parties you trust with arbitrary code execution on your machines.

### 6. accept-flake-config = false

Nix flakes can include a `nixConfig` attribute that requests changes to Nix settings
(extra substituters, sandbox paths, etc). With `accept-flake-config = true` or when
prompted, these settings are applied. A malicious flake could use this to add a
compromised cache or weaken the sandbox.

Setting `accept-flake-config = false` causes Nix to silently ignore all `nixConfig`
attributes in flakes. The approved caches in `trusted-substituters` still work because
they are pre-approved at the system level.

**What breaks:** Flakes that rely on `nixConfig` to configure caches will have those
settings ignored. The devenv flake uses `nixConfig` to request its caches. Fix: pre-approve
those caches in `trusted-substituters` at the system level (which this guide already
recommends).

### 7. filter-syscalls = true

`filter-syscalls` applies a seccomp BPF filter to build processes that prevents creation
of setuid/setgid files, manipulation of POSIX ACLs, and setting extended attributes. These
operations could be used to escalate privileges if a build output were to create a setuid
binary in the Nix store.

The default is `true`. Disabling it removes a defense-in-depth mechanism that prevents a
class of privilege escalation attacks where a malicious derivation places a setuid-root
binary in the Nix store.

**What breaks:** Very rare cases where builds legitimately need setuid. The Nix store is
not the appropriate place for setuid binaries -- NixOS handles setuid wrappers separately
via `security.wrappers`.

### 8. restrict-eval = true (CI servers only)

`restrict-eval` constrains the Nix evaluator to only access files within
`builtins.nixPath` entries and the flake's own source tree. It also restricts network
access during evaluation to URIs matching prefixes in `allowed-uris`.

Without `restrict-eval`, a malicious `.nix` file can read any file the user can read
(`builtins.readFile "/etc/shadow"`) and fetch arbitrary URLs to exfiltrate data during
evaluation.

**WARNING: Not recommended for developer workstations.** `restrict-eval` breaks many
common workflows: fetching new flake inputs, `nix-shell -p`, and devenv.sh's own
evaluation (which requires reading project-local files). Enable it on CI/build servers
where the set of evaluated expressions is known. For developer workstations, use pure
eval (automatic with flakes) and code review of `.nix` files.

### 9. connect-timeout and download-attempts

The default `connect-timeout = 0` means a slow or unresponsive cache can stall builds
indefinitely. Set `connect-timeout = 10` to ensure builds fail fast and fall back to
source builds or alternative caches. Reduce `download-attempts` from 5 to 3 to limit the
window during which a slow cache can hold a build hostage.

**What breaks:** On high-latency connections (satellite, international), 10 seconds may
not be enough. Increase `connect-timeout` to 30 for those environments.

## NixOS Module Snippet

Place in `/etc/nixos/configuration.nix` or a dedicated `nix-hardening.nix` imported by it.

```nix
{ config, lib, ... }:
{
  nix.settings = {
    # Build sandbox: isolate via Linux namespaces, fail if unavailable.
    sandbox = true;
    sandbox-fallback = false;

    # Seccomp filter: block setuid/setgid creation in builds.
    filter-syscalls = true;

    # Require Ed25519 signatures on all binary cache paths.
    require-sigs = true;

    # ONLY root is trusted. No non-root users get root-equivalent access.
    trusted-users = [ "root" ];

    # Restrict Nix daemon access to wheel group members.
    allowed-users = [ "root" "@wheel" ];

    # Pre-approve devenv caches for unprivileged users.
    trusted-substituters = [
{{- range .DefaultCaches }}
      "{{ .URL }}"
{{- end }}
    ];

    # Signing keys for each approved cache.
    trusted-public-keys = [
{{- range .DefaultCaches }}
      "{{ .PublicKey }}"
{{- end }}
    ];

    # Cache connection limits: fail fast, build from source.
    connect-timeout = 10;
    download-attempts = 3;
  };

  # Reject flake nixConfig overrides.
  nix.extraOptions = ''
    accept-flake-config = false
  '';

  # NOTE: restrict-eval is intentionally NOT set here.
  # It breaks interactive devenv usage. Enable on CI/build servers only:
  #   restrict-eval = true;
  #   allowed-uris = [ "https://github.com/NixOS/" "https://github.com/cachix/" "github:" ];
}
```

## Standalone nix.conf

For non-NixOS Linux and macOS. Place at `/etc/nix/nix.conf` (requires root/admin access).
After editing, restart the daemon: `systemctl restart nix-daemon`.

```ini
# /etc/nix/nix.conf -- Hardened configuration for devenv.sh security

# Build sandbox
sandbox = true
sandbox-fallback = false
filter-syscalls = true

# Signature verification
require-sigs = true

# User trust model
trusted-users = root
allowed-users = root @nixbld @wheel

# Binary cache allowlist
substituters = https://cache.nixos.org
trusted-substituters = {{ range .DefaultCaches }}{{ .URL }} {{ end }}
trusted-public-keys = {{ range .DefaultCaches }}{{ .PublicKey }} {{ end }}

# Cache connection limits
connect-timeout = 10
download-attempts = 3

# Flake security
accept-flake-config = false

# Evaluation restrictions (CI/build servers only, uncomment if needed):
# restrict-eval = true
# allowed-uris = https://github.com/NixOS/ https://github.com/cachix/ github: https://cache.nixos.org https://devenv.cachix.org
```

## Per-User nix.conf (~/.config/nix/nix.conf)

Per-user nix.conf is read by the **client**, not the daemon. The client sends requests to
the daemon, and the daemon applies its own security policy. Per-user settings can influence
client-side behavior (like which substituters to request) but **cannot override
daemon-enforced security policies**.

**Settings that work per-user:**
- `extra-substituters` -- request additional caches (only honored if URL is in system
  `trusted-substituters`)
- `extra-trusted-public-keys` -- add verification keys
- `accept-flake-config` -- client-side flake config acceptance
- `warn-dirty` -- warn on dirty Git trees
- `experimental-features` -- enable nix-command, flakes

**Settings that are IGNORED per-user (daemon-enforced):**
- `sandbox`, `sandbox-fallback` -- daemon controls build isolation
- `trusted-users` -- users cannot grant themselves trusted status
- `allowed-users` -- daemon policy
- `require-sigs` -- daemon enforces signature verification
- `filter-syscalls` -- daemon policy for build processes
- `restrict-eval`, `allowed-uris` -- daemon-enforced evaluation restrictions
- `trusted-substituters` -- admin-only cache pre-approval

**Recommended per-user config:**

```ini
# ~/.config/nix/nix.conf
accept-flake-config = false
experimental-features = nix-command flakes
warn-dirty = true
extra-substituters = https://devenv.cachix.org https://cachix.cachix.org
extra-trusted-public-keys = devenv.cachix.org-1:w1cLUi8dv3hnoSPGAuibQv+f9TZLr6cv/Hm9XgU50cw= cachix.cachix.org-1:eWNHQldwUO7G2VkjpnjDbWwy4KQ/HNxht7H4SSoMckM=
```

## Trust Model

| Cache | URL | Signing Key | Purpose |
|-------|-----|-------------|---------|
{{- range .DefaultCaches }}
| {{ .Name }} | {{ .URL }} | `{{ .PublicKey }}` | {{ .Purpose }} |
{{- end }}

Each cache is a trust surface. The signing key holder for a cache can provide arbitrary
binaries for any store path that cache serves. Cache credentials are typically stored in CI
systems where anyone with write access to the repo has read access to the secrets. Minimize
the number of trusted caches to minimize the number of parties you trust with arbitrary
code execution on your machines.

## Deployment Checklist

- [ ] Set `sandbox = true` and `sandbox-fallback = false`
- [ ] Verify `trusted-users` contains ONLY `root`
- [ ] Add devenv caches to `trusted-substituters` (not by adding user to `trusted-users`)
- [ ] Add corresponding signing keys to `trusted-public-keys`
- [ ] Set `accept-flake-config = false`
- [ ] Enable `filter-syscalls = true`
- [ ] Set `connect-timeout = 10` and `download-attempts = 3`
- [ ] Enable `restrict-eval = true` on CI/build servers only
- [ ] Restart the Nix daemon (`systemctl restart nix-daemon`)
- [ ] Test with `devenv shell` to verify cache access works
- [ ] Verify sandbox enforcement: `nix build --sandbox false` as your user should be ignored
